A search for Birds and Song

By Adam Farence

Balliett, setting up his spotting-scope.

Snow crunched underneath Brad Balliett’s boots as he trudged up a slope at Inwood Hill Park in Northern Manhattan. Balliett, wearing a blue-gray jacket, snow pants and an L.L. Bean backpack was searching for birds to inspire his music.

He came equipped with two binoculars, a spotting-scope that he could attach to his phone, and a tripod. Balliett had started on this wintery excursion hoping to spot a peregrine falcon. The falcon, he said with fascination, could reach speeds of over 200 mph.

“There’s a gleam of intelligence in their eyes,” he said, speaking of birds in general. “Everything they do is for a purpose. We’re living side-by-side with these intelligent reptiles.”

Balliett, 38, has a strong relationship with them. He composes music based on birdsong, then creates videos that make it appear the bird is singing Balliett’s piece.

A frequenter of Inwood Hill Park, Balliett often comes to film bird videos he then posts on his Twitter account for followers to play in slow motion.

Animals have always fascinated him. Growing up in Westborough, Massachusetts, he wanted to be a photojournalist for Audubon Society. But other ambitions took over; he grew up to be a musician instead, learning the clarinet, saxophone and violin before eventually settling on the bassoon.

Balliett earned a degree in musical composition from Harvard and a master’s in the bassoon at Rice University. He played in the Houston Symphony for a year before coming to New York City. Now, he teaches at the Peabody Institute at John Hopkins. He’s played with the New York City Ballet, the Metropolitan Opera, the Chamber Music Society of Lincoln Center and the Orpheus Chamber Orchestra.

Animals, he said, disappeared for a long time.

But several years ago, his father suffered from severe respiratory issues and his brother died from colon cancer.  Those losses brought him to a heightened emotional state, he said, which led him back to animals – particularly birds.

“It really felt like falling in love,” Balliett said. “It disrupted my life in the best way possible.”

A close-up of the owl’s nest, as seen through the spotting-scope.

Wondering how to combine his love of music and of birds, he spent two years studying “The Catalogue of the Birds,” a monstrously long composition by the French composer Olivier Messiaen, written between 1956 and 1958. Birdsong inspired, it has a runtime of three hours. Igor Stravinsky and John Coltrane have also heavily influenced Balliett’s music.

He began his own efforts by meticulously creating music based on birdsong, using the bassoon for three birds: the grey catbird, house sparrow and starling.

“I was delighted with the results. It sounded like free jazz,” he said.

What sets Balliett apart from both birders and others who write music based on birdsong, is his videos, in which the birds appear to be singing his compositions.

The pandemic has helped with his birding projects, since he worked from home until he resumed in-person teaching at Peabody in February.

In addition to his own videos, he also posts on Twitter slow-motion videos of birds he takes with his phone mounted to a spotting scope.

Balliett admits that the app, on which tempers often run high, drives him crazy; he’s deleted it at least a dozen times. But using it for bird videos helps him live out his childhood dream of being a photojournalist.

And Balliett’s Twitter videos are quite popular. He has almost 3500 followers, and fans describe his videos as a “bright spot.”

On the way to his first stop, Balliett pointed out the harsh caws of some blue jays who, he said, were likely harassing a hawk.

He stepped off the path and set up his tripod, training the spotting-scope on a nearby tulip tree where a screech owl lives.

Adjusting the scope, he focused on one of the tree’s highest holes, where he normally finds the owl. But the owl wasn’t home – or decided against peering outside.

So Balliett turned his attention to a nearby cliff face and pointed out dozens of smaller birds perched in tree branches.

How does he spot birds? “Let your eyes relax and look for movement,” he said.

The afternoon was partly sunny with little wind and birdwatching continued uninterrupted except when two people slid by on sleds.  At the top of the hill, Balliett pointed out a red-tailed hawk overhead.

“People crave the concentration that birding requires,” Balliett said. “It brings you in the present moment and pushes away everything else in your head.”

His partner of six years, Laura Weiner, who plays the French horn and is pursuing a law degree from SUNY, said Balliett started making videos in mid-March, just days after the World Health Organization declared a pandemic.

The couple headed for a cabin in the Finger Lakes as the coronavirus tightened its grip in the city. There, an avalanche of bad news crashed down on them, as gigs kept getting cancelled and their lives as musicians were upended.

“It was bleak,” Weiner said. “All musicians were now in this weird limbo.”

But in that cabin’s kitchen, Balliett created his first birdsong video: a tufted titmouse appearing to sing to a piece of Balliett’s music.

The slow-motion video starts with the bird perched on a branch with light snow falling. Balliett’s music starts as the bird opens its beak, matches its movements. The video shows three birds in total. A red-winged blackbird and northern flicker follow, also appearing to sing to Balliett’s music. With a total runtime of almost five minutes, the video has almost 200 views on YouTube.

“It was very impressive to me that he dug deep and made these jewels of music,” Weiner said. “They’re so short and poetic.”

Weiner has helped Balliett with some of these videos, and Balliett made a video of a yellow warbler singing to music she helped compose. It was the first bird they saw during the pandemic.

“My memories of those months were tied to those bird videos,” Weiner said.

Now back in their Manhattan home, Weiner says she often gets a sneak peak of Balliett’s bird videos before he releases them –both those with music and without. “I’m always really impressed,” she said. “I know how much time goes into his videos.”

Twitter seems impressed, too. The views for each video he posts often reach into the thousands, accompanied by commentators saying how delighted they are.

The last day in February, Balliett posted a roundup of bird videos he took that month, much to the delight of his Twitter base.

“Nice. Good work, but beyond that, a pleasure to look at,” wrote Sam Seibert, one of Balliett’s many Twitter followers.

After Balliett descended the hill at Inwood Hill Park, he walked to the water’s edge, where he set up his sighting scope and trained it on the Broadway Bridge’s southern tower, zooming in as much as possible.

There, he pointed out the peregrine falcon.
